  "prompt": "Does Java support Multiple Inheritance?",
  "response": "Java does **not** support multiple inheritance in terms of classes, meaning a class cannot inherit from more than one superclass. This design decision helps avoid complexities and ambiguities, such as the \"diamond problem,\" which can arise when multiple parent classes have methods with the same signature.\n\n**However**, Java does support a form of multiple inheritance through the use of **interfaces**. A single Java class can implement multiple interfaces, allowing it to inherit abstract methods (and, since Java 8, default methods) from multiple sources. This provides much of the flexibility of multiple inheritance without the associated complexities.\n\n### Example of Multiple Interface Inheritance\n\n```java\ninterface Flyable {\n    void fly();\n}\n\ninterface Swimmable {\n    void swim();\n}\n\npublic class Duck implements Flyable, Swimmable {\n    @Override\n    public void fly() {\n        System.out.println(\"Duck is flying.\");\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public void swim() {\n        System.out.println(\"Duck is swimming.\");\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Duck duck = new Duck();\n        duck.fly();\n        duck.swim();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example:\n\n- The `Duck` class implements both `Flyable` and `Swimmable` interfaces.\n- It provides concrete implementations for the abstract methods declared in both interfaces.\n- This allows `Duck` to exhibit behaviors defined by multiple interfaces without inheriting from multiple classes.\n\n### Default Methods (Java 8 and Later)\n\nStarting with Java 8, interfaces can include **default methods**, which are methods with a default implementation. This feature allows interfaces to provide additional functionality without breaking existing implementations. It also means that a class implementing multiple interfaces can inherit method implementations from those interfaces.\n\n**Example with Default Methods:**\n\n```java\ninterface A {\n    default void hello() {\n        System.out.println(\"Hello from Interface A\");\n    }\n}\n\ninterface B {\n    default void hello() {\n        System.out.println(\"Hello from Interface B\");\n    }\n}\n\npublic class C implements A, B {\n    @Override\n    public void hello() {\n        // Must override to resolve the conflict between A and B\n        A.super.hello(); // or B.super.hello();\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        C c = new C();\n        c.hello(); // Outputs: Hello from Interface A\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this case:\n\n- Both interfaces `A` and `B` provide a default `hello()` method.\n- Class `C` implements both interfaces and must override the `hello()` method to resolve the conflict, specifying which interface's method to use or providing its own implementation.\n\n### Summary\n\n- **Multiple Class Inheritance:** *Not supported* in Java.\n- **Multiple Interface Inheritance:** *Supported*, allowing a class to implement multiple interfaces.\n- **Default Methods:** Provide a way for interfaces to include method implementations, enhancing the multiple inheritance of behavior through interfaces while avoiding the pitfalls of multiple class inheritance.\n\nThis design strikes a balance between flexibility and simplicity, enabling developers to build complex and modular systems without the complications that true multiple class inheritance can introduce.",
